'''Robert Jeffrey Dover''' (born June 7, 1956 in [[Chicago, Illinois]]) is an American [[Equestrianism|equestrian]] who has had international success in the sport of [[dressage]]. Riding from the age of 13, he began specializing in dressage at age 19 and competed in his first [[Olympic Games|Olympics]] in 1984.  He competed in every summer Games between 1984 and 2004, winning four team bronze medals.  He also took a team bronze at the [[1994 World Equestrian Games]]. Dover is the most honored dressage rider in the United States, and has been inducted to the [[United States Dressage Federation]] Hall of Fame. Outside of competition, Dover founded the Equestrian Aid Foundation in 1996 to assist others in the equestrian world, and hosted a TV show that searched for the next dressage star. From late 2009 to early 2011, Dover served as the Technical/Coach Advisor for the Canadian national dressage team.

==Personal life==
Dover, who is Jewish,<ref name=JVL>{{cite web|url=http://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/biography/dover.html|title=Robert Dover|publisher=Jewish Virtual Library|accessdate=2011-12-09}}</ref> was born in 1956 to parents Herb and Jean Dover.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://doversworld.com/blog/2009/12/15/a-special-issue-of-dovers-world-out-for-good-hero/|author=Dover, Robert|title=A Special Issue Of Dover<U+2019>s World <U+201C>Out For Good Hero<U+201D>|date=December 15, 2009|accessdate=2011-12-09}}</ref> He was given a horse for his Bar Mitzvah at 13 and was active in [[United States Pony Clubs|Pony Club]], graduating at "A" level, the highest level.  He decided to specialize in [[dressage]] when he was 19. Dover attended the [[University of Georgia]].<ref name=HoF>{{cite web|url=http://www.usdf.org/halloffame/inductees/profiles/dover.asp|title=Robert Dover (2008)|publisher=United States Dressage Federation|accessdate=2010-01-30}}</ref><ref name=DN>{{cite web|url=http://www.dressage-news.com/?p=3601|title=Robert Dover Canada's New National Coach|author=Braddick, Kenneth J.|date=October 7, 2009|accessdate=2010-01-30|publisher=Dressage News}}</ref> He is openly [[gay]], and his partner is fellow rider Robert Ross.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nbcsports.msnbc.com/id/5724361/|title=Many gay Olympians remain cautious|publisher=NBC Sports|accessdate=2010-03-27}}</ref> Injuries, including a torn [[rotator cuff]] and pinched [[sciatic nerve]], began to plague him in the late 1990s, causing major back pain and reducing his ability to ride.<ref name=JVL/>

==Career==
===Competition===

In 1984, Dover competed in his first Olympic Games at the age of 28. At the [[Equestrian at the 1984 Summer Olympics|Los Angeles Games]], he finished 17th individually, and the US team finished 6th. At the 1988 [[Equestrian at the 1988 Summer Olympics|Seoul Olympics]], he finished 13th, and the team tied for 6th place. In 1992, at the [[Equestrian at the 1992 Summer Olympics|Barcelona Games]], Dover tied for 22nd place, while the American team took the bronze medal. At the 1996 [[Equestrian at the 1996 Summer Olympics|Atlanta Games]], the 2000 [[Equestrian at the 2000 Summer Olympics|Sydney Olympics]] and the 2004 [[Equestrian at the 2004 Summer Olympics|Athina Games]] the United States dressage team took the bronze medal each time, while Dover finished 25th, 23rd and 6th respectively.<ref name=SR>{{cite web|url=http://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/do/robert-dover-1.html|title=Robert Dover|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=2010-01-30}}</ref> He was elected team captain in all six Olympics in which he competed.<ref name=DN/> Of his Olympic experience, Dover says, "The medals themselves aren't the important thing. My memories of the Games and of the entire Olympic experience are, to me, everything."<ref>{{cite book|title=Olympic Equestrian: The Sports and the Stories from Stockholm to Sydney|author=Bryant, Jennifer O.|year=2000|publisher=The Blood-Horse, Inc|isbn=1581500440|page=222}}</ref>

In 1987, Dover defeated [[Reiner Klimke]], a six-time Olympic gold medalist, at the German Aachen Grand Prix freestyle competition. In doing so, he became the first American in 27 years to win that event.<ref name=DN/> In 1994 he was named the US Olympic Male Equestrian Athlete of the Year, and in 1995 awarded the Whitney Stone Cup, given by the [[United States Equestrian Federation]] (USEF) for excellence in international competition. Dover has been named the USEF Dressage Champion five times, and ridden seven times in the [[International Federation for Equestrian Sports|FEI]] World Cup Final.<ref name=HoF/> In 1994, Dover rode with the United States dressage team at the [[1994 World Equestrian Games|World Equestrian Games]], winning a team bronze.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://twww.fei.org/sites/default/files/file/EVENTS/GAMES/FEI%20WORLD%20EQUESTRIAN%20GAMES/Results/The_Hague_1994/WEG1994_Dressage_Team.pdf|title=Dressage - Team Championship|format=PDF|accessdate=2011-01-22|publisher=FEI}}</ref> He was also amassed more than 100 Grand Prix victories.<ref name=DN/> Overall, Dover has won more honors in dressage than any other rider from the United States.<ref name=HoF/> In 2009, Dover announced his retirement from competitive riding, instead choosing to focus on teaching and philanthropy.<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Practical Horseman|title=USDF HOF inducts Dover, Baan|date=January 2009|page=69}}</ref>

===Other===

Dover founded the Equestrian Aid Foundation in 1996. The Foundation's mission is to financially assist members of the equestrian community who have suffered a catastrophic accident, injury or illness.<ref name=HoF/> In 2002, Dover was listed as one of the 50 most influential horsemen by ''Chronicle of the Horse'' magazine.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.thehorse.com/ViewArticle.aspx?ID=1510|title=Most Influential Horsemen Announced|format=Registration required|accessdate=2010-01-30|journal=The Horse|date=October 11, 2002|author=Church, Stephanie L.}}</ref> In 2007, "The Search for America's Next Equestrian Star: Dressage", a reality TV show created and promoted by Dover, aired on the Fox Reality Channel with five one-hour episodes.<ref name=HoF/> The show followed a search for young, talented dressage riders, with the final five being allowed to train with Dover for one month before a winner was selected; the winner became Dover's assistant.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Dressage star search!|journal=Practical Horseman|author=Jaffer, Nancy|date=February 2005|page=17}}</ref> In 2008, Dover was inducted into the [[United States Dressage Federation]] Hall of Fame. Dover served on the USEF Dressage Committee for many years, and spent eight years on the US Olympic Committee Athlete Advisory Council.<ref name=HoF/>  

In late 2009, Dover was selected as a Technical/Coach Advisor for the Canadian dressage team,<ref name=DN/> with a contract that extended through the [[2010 World Equestrian Games]] in [[Lexington, Kentucky]]. After the Games, it was announced that Dover and the Canadian team had not been able to agree on contract renewal terms,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dressage-news.com/?p=8891|title=Robert Dover and Dressage Canada Split|publisher=Dressage News|accessdate=2011-01-22|date=October 31, 2010}}</ref> but in late 2010 it was announced that Dover would remain as the interim trainer for the first quarter of 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dressage-news.com/?p=9330|title=Robert Dover Rehired as Interim Dressage Canada Coach|publisher=Dressage News|accessdate=2011-01-22|date=December 17, 2010}}</ref> In March 2011, German equestrian Markus Gribbe was hired, and Dover's term as a Canadian coach came to an end.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.horse-canada.com/horse-news/new-dressage-canada-high-performance-program-technical-leader/|title=New Dressage Canada High Performance Program Technical Leader|date=March 24, 2011|publisher=Horse Canada|accessdate=2011-12-09}}</ref> Dover is known for his coaching abilities, with some of the best dressage riders with top international titles to their credit coming from his stables. During his time as a trainer for Canada, he was no longer be eligible to train top riders with the USEF.<ref name=DN/> Dover is currently a rider and trainer at Stillpoint Farm in [[Florida]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stillpointfarmdressage.com/Trainers%20at%20Stillpoint%20Farm.htm|title=Trainers in residence|publisher=Stillpoint Farm|accessdate=2011-12-09}}</ref>

